                      <td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="verdana" size="2" color="white"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> Milgram,<br /><br />To answer your question simply: No.  We are talking about a pretty small advantage with high charisma, to a point.  <br /><br />I have found it fairly difficult to quantify with any certainty exactly how much of a boon it is at various levels.  This leads me to believe that it is on a sliding scale and not a fixed one.  At 250+ charisma I started noticing a dramatic increase in charm durations.  At 305 charisma Word of Terris actually stayed on the mob for full duration AFTER tash/malos wore off, on several occasions (this never happens with a normal charisma score.. tash wears off and the mob is attacking you the very next round).<br /><br />None of this was garnered while performing actual tests.  I have far more enjoyable and profitable things to do than sit around for hours on end testing a game that I pay to play.  I am speaking from my experiences, countless hours spent charming mobs in various zones, of various levels, for various reasons.  Since the charm nerf I always have either a shaman or enchanter with me while charming, hence the access to debuffs and charisma buff.<br /><br />If you never use charisma buffs you can still charm and charm well.  Using charisma buffs, by my experience, will really only help you if you can get your score to 250+ or perhaps at least close to 250.  Even then, if you have to sacrifice too much gear to get that score you may be hurting yourself more than helping.  <br /><br />Flame on squirrel brains.<br /><br />Vtyn<br />Arch Lich<br />Heaven and Earth</span id="msg"></font></td>
                    </tr>
